{
  "texts": [
    "As a baseline, when there is no discount from using AI (discount rate is 1), then as expected public knowledge converges to the true distribution, 9 As AI reduces the cost of truncated knowledge, however, the distribution of public knowledge collapses towards the center, with tail knowledge being under-represented.",
    "Under these conditions, excessive reliance 7 Zamora (2010) suggests a scientific process of 'verisimiltude', where we judge evidence not with reference to objective truth by by \"perceived closeness to what we empirically know about the truth, weighted by the perceived amount of information this empirical knowledge contains\" (Zamora-Bonilla 2010).",
    "Work on human cultural transmission attempts to explain, for example, how the Tasmanians lost a number of useful technologies over time.",
    "(Mesoudi and Whiten 2008; Henrich 2004) 8 For example, Christian communities at times actively promoted and preserved 'canonical' texts while neglecting or banning others, with the result that those excluded from reproduction by scribes were taken to have little value.",
    "Perhaps the heliocentric view espoused by Aristarchus of Samos in the 3rd century BCE would have been more readily (re)considered if his works had not been neglected (Russo and others 2003)."
  ]
